Or you can do Swedish "återställare" (roughly "reset button") and just have a beer after you wake up! You get drunk again depending on how much you had the night before. Since the processing of alcohol never stops, you won't have to bare the pain of being hungover, and instead you can slowly ease off the alcohol and feel better (in a few hours).

Not recommended if you have work or want to drive a car the day after drinking, although you probably shouldn't get behind the wheel of a motor vehicle if you feel the need to återställa yourself haha.

Surely if you (as a taxi company) are going to have to dig up a parking lot to install the wireless charging coils any way, it would be more efficient to have some kind of automatic mechanical arm rise up and physically connect to the underside of the vehicle to provide power? Far less waste of energy and an arm could have adjustments so it can compensate if the vehicle isn't 100% spot-on over the charging zone.

Ultimately, the full hands-off self-driving aspect with zero manual controls won't come to pass for a long time to come yet. Until every single vehicle on the road has full self-driving capability there's too much risk mixing self-driving with human-operated vehicles. And I really can't imagine the regulations will change any time soon to allow zero manual control overrides - not even in the next decade or two, let alone handful of years. Commercial passenger planes (like 737s etc) have technically been able to take-off, fly and land entirely autonomously for quite a long time now and yet they STILL all have manual controls and they STILL have the human pilots perform the take-offs and landings because as sophisticated as the computer systems are, they don't cope with unusual or "new" situations at all (or errors in their software which absolutely can and does happen) and will always 'give up' and expect the human to take over.
